the Ô¨Ånal model. The estimates of the ecosystem type parameters were higher for upwellings than tropical and temperate ecosystems, in accordance with the transfer efÔ¨Åciency we used to calculate PPR.
The prediction of Primary Production Required in each LME was reasonably accurate (Normalized Root Mean Square Error = 12%). The model prediction of global PPR was 3.74 ¬∑ 109 t C year)1 which is very similar to the actual PPR computed from the data (3.46 ¬∑ 109 t C year)1). More sustainable Ô¨Åsheries would decrease the PPR, the negative coefÔ¨Åcient suggests PPR signiÔ¨Åcantly decreased with higher values of Psust (Table 1). Exploitation of smaller-bodied Ô¨Åshes results in greater Ô¨Åsheries catch; the negative coefÔ¨Åcient shows that PPR signiÔ¨Åcantly decreased with Lmax (Table 1). Primary production appears to constrain Ô¨Åsheries catches since PP positively and signiÔ¨Åcantly affects PPR, once ecosystem type, degree of Ô¨Åsheries exploitation (Psust), and intrinsic population growth (Lmax) are accounted for (Table 1).
Primary production as a limiting factor of Ô¨Åsheries catch
Primary production limits average and maximum Ô¨Åsheries catch across the world at the LME scale over both short and longer time scales (Fig. 1a, c and S2). The limitation has become increasingly apparent as regression slopes become steeper in more recent time periods (Fig. 2). The signiÔ¨Åcant relationship found between long-term (1950‚Äì2004) and recent catch (2000‚Äì2004) (slope = 0.76, adjusted r2 = 0.82, P < 0.001) revealed that the spatial gradients in fisheries catches were consistent through time (Figs S3 and S4).
Increasing levels of Ô¨Åshing exploitation through time
There has been a steady increase in the level of exploitation (PPR ‚ÅÑ PP) with a maximum value of 16% during 2000‚Äì 2004, based on the change in the 90% quantile regression slope (Figs 3 and S5). The stability of the PPR ‚ÅÑ PP ratio in

the last 20 years could suggest that current Ô¨Åshing patterns, and especially the Ô¨Åshing strategy currently applied in term of trophic levels that are targeted, may not allow any further increase in LME Ô¨Åsheries catch relative to primary production levels.
Predictions of maximum global Ô¨Åsheries catch
The potential maximum of global catch in the LMEs was predicted to be 146 ¬∑ 106 t year)1 during 2000‚Äì2004 based on the 90% quantile regression model ( Table 2). The mean total catch during 2000‚Äì2004 exceeded the maximum global Ô¨Åsheries catch predicted from the Large Marine Ecosystems where Ô¨Åshing is considered sustainable by 17% and 112% for Psust > 75% and Psust > 95%, respectively (Table 2). These results emphasize the dependence of the current levels of Ô¨Åsheries catch on the unsustainable exploitation of these Large Marine Ecosystems.
DISCUSSION
Linkage between primary production and Ô¨Åsheries catches
Globally, Ô¨Åsheries catches are increasingly constrained by the primary productivity of the underlying Large Marine Ecosystems (Pauly & Christensen 1995). While this has been shown at regional scales (Ware & Thomson 2005; Chassot et al. 2007), the novelty of the present work is to show that primary production constrains Ô¨Åsheries catches worldwide, while accounting for ecosystem and Ô¨Åsheries features. Here, we show that the primary production appropriated by Ô¨Åsheries catches depends on the scale and nature of Ô¨Åsheries, with heavily exploited Ô¨Åsheries and those Ô¨Åsheries targeting the smallest Ô¨Åsh species appropriating more primary production per tonne of catch. In addition, comparison of long-term vs. recent catches showed that the regional gradients in Ô¨Åsheries catches have not been modiÔ¨Åed during the last half century, in spite of different

